<p>Giving a talk that‚Äôs aligned with your motivations is helpful in several ways:</p>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>It‚Äôs easier to pick a topic.</strong> My formula is ‚Äúexplain an inspiring idea and why you should care about it‚Äù. I can create talk proposals by applying this formula to any interesting concept that I learned. I‚Äôll always have something to talk about as long as I‚Äôm listening to smart people with good ideas that deserve more exposure. There are many other possible formulas ‚Äî find yours.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>It‚Äôs less scary on stage.</strong> I get terrified 30 seconds before the talk but <em>the moment I start talking, I‚Äôm in my element</em>. The drive to share an inspiring idea overtakes the fear of being judged or doing something wrong. (Of course, this only works with good preparation which we‚Äôll talk about in the next posts.)</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>It‚Äôs more convincing.</strong> I can‚Äôt phrase it better than <a href=\\"https://mobile.twitter.com/sophiebits/status/1077723835481284608\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\\">Sophie did</a>: if you‚Äôre enthusiastic about a topic, you can get the audience to care too. Enthusiasm doesn‚Äôt necessarily mean being loud or waving hands. Even if you‚Äôre calm, people can feel when there‚Äôs an emotional conviction behind a talk. (This is also why we can vibe to a <a href=\\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6SWIwW9mg8s\\" target=\\"_blank\\" rel=\\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\\">song</a> even if we don‚Äôt understand the words.)</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<p>There‚Äôs one more reason it helps when you‚Äôre genuinely excited about a topic. Feeling that you‚Äôre a part of something bigger does wonders for confidence.</p>
<p>My talks aren‚Äôt about <em>me</em> ‚Äî they‚Äôre about an idea, and I‚Äôm just a messenger. Thousands of people on the livestream and in the audience aren‚Äôt really there to judge me (even if they think so). They came to experience the idea that I brought to share. My role is just to be a conduit from one mind to another. A lot of nerves and pressure from the talks disappeared after internalizing this.</p>
<hr>
<p>Finding a formula that‚Äôs consistent with your motivations helps you establish your own voice. But how do you find a <em>specific</em> topic to which you can apply it?</p>
<p><strong>In my experience, good talks start as conversations.</strong> Somebody explains an idea to me, and then I try to explain it to someone else. I talk about it to a dozen people, and eventually I find explanations that ‚Äúclick‚Äù. Sometimes there‚Äôs a thought that seems neglected or misunderstood, and I try to get individual people to see it in a different light.</p>
<p>For me, a talk is just a way to generalize those conversations and make them one-to-many rather than one-to-one. It‚Äôs like a ‚Äúlibrary‚Äù you extract out of the ‚Äúapplication code‚Äù of many in-person and social media conversations.</p>
<p>So if you want to give a great talk, <em>talking</em> to people is a good way to start.</p>
