          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\">I went to a two-day √¢‚Ç¨≈ìD&I workshop for leaders√¢‚Ç¨¬ù. Many in biz will know what that stands for: Diversity and Inclusion. The people facilitating were<a href=\\"https://www.wmfdp.com/\\">WMFDP</a>, which stands for √¢‚Ç¨≈ìWhite Men as Full Diversity Partners√¢‚Ç¨¬ù. Having said that, only one of the two was a white man, and the audience was more gender-diverse than the high-tech norm.  Everyone was senior, there were lots of VPs in the room. It had a strong effect on me.</div>",
        },
        "content" => Object {
          "attrs": Map {
            "type" => "xhtml",
          },
          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\"><p>I went to a two-day √¢‚Ç¨≈ìD&I workshop for leaders√¢‚Ç¨¬ù. Many in biz will know what that stands for: Diversity and
Inclusion. The people facilitating were<a href=\\"https://www.wmfdp.com/\\">WMFDP</a>, which stands for √¢‚Ç¨≈ìWhite Men as Full Diversity Partners√¢‚Ç¨¬ù. Having said that, only one of
the two was a white man, and the audience was more gender-diverse than the high-tech norm.
Everyone was senior, there were lots of VPs in the room. It had a strong effect on me.</p><h2 id=\\"p-1\\">Truths</h2><p>In the technology space, we suck at diversity.  We√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re broadly better than average at LGBTQ, probably not far off the mainstream
at Under-Represented Minorities, and terrible at gender.  Tech leadership is by and large aware of the problem, takes it seriously,
and would be very happy if there were a lever they could pull to fix it.  They are investing considerable energy,
including a nontrivial amount of leadership time, a very scarce resource.</p><h2 id=\\"p-3\\">Reportage</h2><p>I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve been trying for weeks to figure out my take on the workshop, turn it into a nice narrative with a story arc
and Big Lessons.  That hasn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t worked. But when I went back to review my notes I found a few really resonated.
So what the hell, here are the ones I think worth reading.  Draw your own conclusions.</p><p>Some of these are what the facilitators were saying. Some of them are quotes from other people. Some are
me talking to myself.  They start out pretty business-y but get personal.</p><ol><li><p>We were trying to close a $100M deal, and the customer wanted to see our D&I numbers, including diversity among our
suppliers.</p></li><li><p>In hiring, look for √¢‚Ç¨≈ìReturnees√¢‚Ç¨¬ù, people who√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve taken a break and want to come back to work. In
practical terms, these are almost all women who√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve been doing family caregiving.</p></li><li><p>Shortening the list of qualifications in job postings can be useful, because of men√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s propensity to be aspirational in
describing their qualifications.</p></li><li><p>When we get women into the interview process, we hire them at the same rate as men. So we need to interview more.</p></li><li><p>I am the tech business. I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve had all the jobs, done all the things. If a diverse population  doesn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t want to join it, I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m what
they don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t want to join.</p></li><li><p>If you look at the Fortune 500√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s diversity programs, they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re basically all led by women.  So we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re asking the outsider group
to do all the work of fixing the discrimination against them.  A few white guys running some of these things might not be a terrible
thing.  There√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a parallel with husbands who say they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re happy to help at home but ask their wives to do all the hard emotional/logistical
work.</p></li><li><p>The evidence of bias and anti-diversity prejudice is statistically overwhelming, no matter how many individual leaders deny
having it.</p></li><li><p>Men will remain indifferent unless they perceive they will benefit from D&I.</p></li><li><p>In tech, the bias is present and measurable, but is rarely explicit or intentional, and the people who empirically<em>must</em>be responsible will hotly deny being part of the problem. (But maybe less so based on attendance at this
exercise?)</p></li><li><p>People don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t know how to talk about it. Talking about it is difficult, and that√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s OK.</p></li><li><p>Short meetings are a form of discrimination<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞shy people don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t get words in.</p></li><li><p>This black guy in the sales organization, super senior and successful, says √¢‚Ç¨≈ìI haven√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t told anybody, but I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve been keeping
count, in meetings, of black people among the customers at my level. Still haven√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t got to ten.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù</p></li><li><p>√¢‚Ç¨≈ìInsider culture√¢‚Ç¨¬ù<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞individualism<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞low tolerance for
uncertainty<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞action vs reflection<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞rationality
over emotion<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞time is linear and future-focused<span class=\\"dashes\\">√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞√¢‚Ç¨‚Äù</span>√¢‚Ç¨‚Ä∞status and rank win over
correctness.</p></li><li><p>The ultimate privilege is being listened to.</p></li><li><p>When I mentor people, should I encourage them to be more like me?</p></li><li><p>Who should be teaching about male privilege? Ideally not always women.</p></li><li><p>Women say they have to do a<em>lot</em>more thinking before they get their clothes on and walk out the door.</p></li><li><p>So disappointed at the times I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve heard √¢‚Ç¨≈ìI√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m used to it.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù</p></li><li><p>Insiders are identified as individuals, not as members of a group.</p></li><li><p>It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s totally reasonable for outsiders to see me as √¢‚Ç¨≈ìjust another white guy√¢‚Ç¨¬ù.</p></li><li><p>It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not my fault but I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m responsible.</p></li></ol><h2 id=\\"p-5\\">A conversation</h2><p>In one of the exercises, we were in smallish groups and were asked: √¢‚Ç¨≈ìEveryone look inside themselves and find a dimension along
which you√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re an outsider.  Say a few words on what that is and how you feel about it.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù  Well√¢‚Ç¨¬¶ I came up empty, and said so.  I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m
white, male, live in the nation where I was born, straight, able-bodied, well-paid, lucky, and have mainstream tastes.</p><p>There was a short uneasy silence. Then this smart,
polished, accomplished, person who unlike me is<em>not</em>an insider-on-every-axis looked me in the eye and said √¢‚Ç¨≈ìSo, why are you
here?√¢‚Ç¨¬ù  The honest truth is I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m really freaking sick of spending all my time in rooms full of men, so I said that but it felt
unsatisfactory.  I looked for something deeper to say but came up empty.</p><h2 id=\\"p-2\\">My crazy idea</h2><p>I think we in big tech companies should publicly face down our problems, starting with the worst ones.  To start with,
I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢d like us to disclose the actual gender-diversity numbers in our engineering organizations and take a public goal of
changing them, say by 5% over a couple of years, and then disclose the results.</p><p>Because here√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s the thing: The people in the management
ranks in big tech are, by and large, pretty smart and resourceful.  Tell them they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re going to be judged on any given number,
and they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ll figure out a way to move that number in the right direction.</p><p>√¢‚Ç¨≈ìIt√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not my fault but I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m responsible.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù</p></div>",
