          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\">That√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s over a hundred kilometers of course, which it took three days to achieve.</div>",
        },
        "content" => Object {
          "attrs": Map {
            "type" => "xhtml",
          },
          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\"><p>That√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s over a hundred kilometers of course, which it took three days to achieve.</p><ol><li><p>I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m enjoying learning how to deploy that electric-Jag power gracefully.  Yeah, you can floor it, which
is shocking if brutish fun and might damage your neck vertebrae. But you know what√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s way sweeter? Coming out of a
corner, or around a slower car, and easing the accelerator down, and then further and further down,<em>smoothly</em>. You can√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t do
this for more than a few seconds without being in seriously unlawful territory anywhere this side of the Autobahn, but oh my
goodness those are really very pleasing seconds; the pool of acceleration is bottomless.</p></li><li><p>I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve had two charging experiences so far (haven√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t needed any, just trying to learn the ropes), both from<a href=\\"https://www.chargepoint.com/en-ca/\\">ChargePoint</a>, both perfectly smooth. You plug in the big heavy connector, fire up
the app, hold your phone up to the machine, and away it goes.</p><p>But I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m glad I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m going to have my own charger before the month is over, because the √¢‚Ç¨≈ìfast√¢‚Ç¨¬ù chargers like the one illustrated here
are in demand and not well maintained; of the two in the picture, one is out of order and apparently has been for a couple of
months</p></li><img src=\\"https://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/201x/2019/01/15/IMG_20190117_170440.png\\" alt=\\"I-Pace at fast charger\\"/><img src=\\"https://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/201x/2019/01/15/IMG_20190117_170532.png\\" alt=\\"I-Pace, fast charger and its infrastructure\\"/><div class=\\"caption\\"><p>Above, charging in progress; below, another angle. The black box at the right below is supporting infrastructure;
the label on the side says 80A worth of 3-cycle power.</p></div><li><p>There√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve been stories of people having trouble getting their I-Paces to connect to one charger model or another, but I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve
had none on two out of two experiences.  The √¢‚Ç¨≈ìfast charger√¢‚Ç¨¬ù took me from 86% to 96% full in a half-hour.  (That√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s 11.26 kWh, or
almost exactly one Canadian dollar√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s worth at<a href=\\"https://app.bchydro.com/accounts-billing/rates-energy-use/electricity-rates/residential-rates.html\\">residential rates</a>.)
This is not as lame
as it sounds, because the charging speed declines as the battery fills up, notably slowing down past 80%.  Thus, when on
a road trip, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s considered to be smart and courteous, at a roadside fast-charger, to unplug and go at 80%.</p></li><li><p>The turning radius is large, bigger than our old Honda van√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s.  Maybe something to do with the wheels being
pushed out to the corners? This is particularly annoying because any fool can get into the rhythm of jamming a shift-stick back and
forth between Drive/1st and R while three-pointing on a narrow street, but my fingers are nowhere near learning how to hit the Jag√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s
D and R buttons without looking.</p></li><img src=\\"https://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/201x/2019/01/15/seat.png\\" alt=\\"I-Pace car seat adjustments\\"/><li><p>I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m dealing with angst about the seat position; it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a paradox-of-choice problem, there are just too many
controls.  I may have to go all engineer and take a systematic approach, making one change at a time on one lever at a
time.  I should be clear that it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a fabulously comfortable seat, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s just that I can√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t prove it couldn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t be better.</p></li><li><p>The √¢‚Ç¨≈ìPark Assist√¢‚Ç¨¬ù feature, which has two dedicated buttons, doesn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t work.  It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not just me, I<a href=\\"https://www.ipaceforums.co.uk/viewtopic.php?f=8&t=905\\">asked my peers</a>and everyone agrees that yeah, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s just
broken. Shame on Jaguar, other modern cars get this right. I wonder if it can be fixed in software?</p></li><li><p>In fact, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a good thing that the I-Pace is so much fun to drive, because it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s generally a pain in the ass to park.  The
visibility through the tiny dim near-horizontal back window is laughable, the rear-view camera is a little laggy (great picture
though), and the car is wide.  I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m sure I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ll figure out a way to curve into place, reasonably close to and parallel to the curb, but
I haven√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t yet.</p></li><li><p>Driving my fossil car to work was dumb and this one being electric doesn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t change that.  Parking is still
expensive, as are the L2 chargers in Vancouver office-building basements.</p></li></ol></div>",
        },
