        "summary" => Object {
          "attrs": Map {
            "type" => "xhtml",
          },
          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\">Well obviously: Frugality, security, and elasticity.  But I want more, I want<em>better software</em>.</div>",
        },
        "content" => Object {
          "attrs": Map {
            "type" => "xhtml",
          },
          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\"><p>Well obviously: Frugality, security, and elasticity.  But I want more, I want<em>better software</em>.</p><p><i>[This is part of the<a href=\\"/ongoing/When/201x/2018/12/09/Serverlessness\\">Serverlessness</a>series.]</i></p><h2 id=\\"p-1\\">Frugality</h2><p>The core idea is that when your workload goes to zero, so does your bill.  You might save big;<a href=\\"https://aws.amazon.com/solutions/case-studies/financial-engines/\\">Financial Engines</a>is the first case study that Google
popped up for me, but I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve heard muttered stories in the hallways about way bigger savings than that.  And then there√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s my co-worker
who took his school-photographer wife√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s Website billings from $10/month down to a few cents.</p><p>And we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re not just talking about Lambda.  When there are no messages flowing through your SQS queue, you√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re not paying
anything. When your Step Functions workflow is waiting, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s just a row in a database. And so on and so on.</p><img src=\\"https://www.tbray.org/ongoing/When/201x/2018/12/10/DsEx9t5U0AASIlI.png\\" alt=\\"From Werner Vogels√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ 2017 re:invent keynote\\"/><div class=\\"caption\\"><p>Disclosure: I lobbied to get that soundbite into that keynote.</p></div><h2 id=\\"p-2\\">Security</h2><p>When you can√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t see the servers, that means we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re taking care of them.  And since servers fail, our services have to be designed to
survive restarts. Which means that we can (and do) bounce them whenever they need patching.  So whatever hosts your DynamoDB table
or your SNS topic is running on, they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re likely freshly-enough patched to cut the number of known vulnerabilities to just about the
minimum possible.<i>[Urgh, upon typing this, it occurred to me to check the uptime on the Linux box hosting
this blog, and it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s like a year. The box generating the bits you are now reading is probably a soft target for
all the bad guys out there. Ahem.]</i></p><p>Anyhow, there√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s no perfect security in this bad old world, but freshly-patched instances really do help a lot.</p><h2 id=\\"p-3\\">Elasticity</h2><p>When we deliver serverless services, what we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re really trying to do is get you out of the business of capacity
forecasting. That business<em>sucks</em>.  It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s hard, and easy to get wrong; the penalty for estimating low is lousy
performance for your customers, and estimating high is throwing away money.  So go serverless and let us take care of that for
you.</p><p>(By the way, I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m not claiming that we√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re any smarter about capacity management than you are. When you aggregate all the AWS
customers√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ traffic, the lumpy local variations even out.  So it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a much easier problem if you√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re a public-cloud
provider. Of course you have to not mind billions in capex.)</p><h2 id=\\"p-4\\">What about software quality?</h2><p>As<a href=\\"/ongoing/When/201x/2018/07/31/Serverless-Economics\\">I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ve blogged before</a>, that √¢‚Ç¨≈ìFrugality, Security, Elasticity√¢‚Ç¨¬ù pitch
operates at a more or less pure business level.  But I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m a technologist and engineer, so I have to ask,
are serverless application designs<em>better</em>designs?  I think the only honest answer is √¢‚Ç¨≈ìWe don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t know yet.√¢‚Ç¨¬ù</p><p>Having
said that, my gut is saying √¢‚Ç¨≈ìyes√¢‚Ç¨¬ù.  It helps that I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m an old functional-programming bigot, and the notion of stateless functions in
the cloud responding to events gives me a warm glow.  There are things we<em>do</em>know: microservices that are connected
asynchronously with messaging systems (e.g. SQS, 100% serverless) are more robust and flexible than those that aren√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t.  But√¢‚Ç¨¬¶ Can I
say we have a basis of experience sufficiently strong to say √¢‚Ç¨≈ìServerless software is better√¢‚Ç¨¬ù?  Nope.</p><p>But I√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢m pretty sure that going serverless isn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t going to give you a<em>worse</em>design. So you should bloody well go ahead and
do it, because: Frugality, Security, and Elasticity.</p><h2 id=\\"p-5\\">But wait√¢‚Ç¨¬¶</h2><p>Look at that picture above from Werner Vogels√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢ keynote at the 2017 re:Invent.</p><p>Then consider the fact that you have a finite time budget for software design.  If you go serverless, then you you don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t
have to design Kubernetes flows or Auto Scaling policies or fleet-health metrics or any of that other stuff.  All your design time
can be dedicated to, like Werner√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s slide says, software that directly addresses business issues.  So, given more design time, you√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re<em>probably</em>gonna get a better design with serverless.</p><p>My feeling is, the<em>why</em>of serverless is pretty obvious. It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s the<em>how</em>that√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s interesting.</p></div>",
