          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\">I don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t think it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s<em>that</em>complicated: If you can√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t see the servers in the service, then it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s serverless.  Yeah, they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re still there, but the<em>whole point</em>is that you can mostly not worry about them.</div>",
        },
        "content" => Object {
          "attrs": Map {
            "type" => "xhtml",
          },
          "meta": Map {},
          "uri": "http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom",
          "value": "<div xmlns=\\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\\"><p>I don√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t think it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s<em>that</em>complicated: If you can√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t see the servers in the service, then it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s serverless.  Yeah, they√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢re
still there, but the<em>whole point</em>is that you can mostly not worry about them.</p><p><i>[This is part of the<a href=\\"/ongoing/When/201x/2018/12/09/Serverlessness\\">Serverlessness</a>series.]</i></p><p>That doesn√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢t work just for functions: Lots of
services, for example RDS (in certain flavors), ElasticSearch, and Amazon MQ, require that you pick an instance that the service runs
on before you start.  Let√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s extend the nomenclature a bit; if anything requires that you pre-provision IOPS (or other unit of
capacity), then that√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not so serverless.</p><img src=\\"MQ-broker.png\\" alt=\\"Launching an Amazon MQ broker\\"/><div class=\\"caption\\"><p>It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s a great service, but it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not serverless.</p></div><h2 id=\\"p-2\\">Etymology</h2><p>Several people, starting with Werner Vogels, have griped about the name √¢‚Ç¨≈ìserverless√¢‚Ç¨¬ù, finding it ill-conceived and pointed in the
wrong direction, preferring positive rather than negative names.  Fair enough, but too bad, English is not just a living language
but a hasty, impulsive, pigheaded one, and it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s settled on √¢‚Ç¨≈ìServerless√¢‚Ç¨¬ù now, so just deal.</p><p>By the way, any fool can plainly see that the opposite of Serverless is Serverful, with just one trailing √¢‚Ç¨≈ìl√¢‚Ç¨¬ù, just like
faithful, sinful, and skillful.</p><h2 id=\\"p-1\\">It√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s not binary</h2><p>I heartily recommend Ben Kehoe√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s<a href=\\"https://read.acloud.guru/the-serverless-spectrum-147b02cb2292\\">The Serverless Spectrum</a>in support of this point.  Let
me illustrate by example:  Your basic enterprise Oracle deployment is the most serverful thing imaginable; with the primary,
fallback, and standby instances, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s<em>triply</em>serverful!
RDS Aurora Serverless is more serverless, and while DynamoDB has always been even more serverless, with the advent of<a href=\\"https://aws.amazon.com/blogs/aws/amazon-dynamodb-on-demand-no-capacity-planning-and-pay-per-request-pricing/\\">On-Demand
mode</a>, it√¢‚Ç¨‚Ñ¢s<em>really</em>serverless.</p><p>Another example: An EC2 instance is hardly serverless, a Docker container launched in Fargate is really pretty serverless, while
a Lambda function is the epitome of serverlessness.</p><p>I think we are past the time to argue about what √¢‚Ç¨≈ìserverless√¢‚Ç¨¬ù means.</p></div>",
